e über Homosexualität.  aThe Catholic Church still takes an ambivalent stance toward homosexuality, declaring that homosexuals should be respected and not discriminated against while morally condemning their intimate relationships. This volume presents exegetical, theological, and ethical arguments as well as evidence from the human sciences to advocate for the recognition of homosexuality as a natural variant of the human capacities to love and to form relationships.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aGaysxReligious life. 0aHomosexualityxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 4aExegese. 4aKatholische Lehre. 4aKatholische Theologie. 4aTheologische Ethik. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh  aBiblical Criticism.  aCatholic Ethics.  aCatholic Theology.1 aBosinski, Hartmut A. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoertz, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoertz, Stephan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHieke, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilpert, Konrad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawler, Michael G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarschütz, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiedlich, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalzman, Todd A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteffens, Melanie Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStriet, Magnus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTheobald, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/